Here's how to handle draft persistence across app lifecycle events in .NET MAUI:

**1. In your `App.xaml.cs`, hook lifecycle events:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    public App()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        MainPage = new AppShell();
    }

    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Deactivated += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Fires when app goes to background
            MessagingCenter.Send<App>(this, "AppBackgrounded");
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Fires when app returns to foreground
            MessagingCenter.Send<App>(this, "AppResumed");
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. In your notes page view model or code-behind:**

```csharp
public partial class NotesPage : ContentPage
{
    private readonly Editor _editor;

    public NotesPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        _editor = NoteEditor; // Named in XAML

        // Restore draft on load
        _editor.Text = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);

        MessagingCenter.Subscribe<App>(this, "AppBackgrounded", (sender) =>
        {
            SaveDraft();
        });

        MessagingCenter.Subscribe<App>(this, "AppResumed", (sender) =>
        {
            RestoreDraft();
        });
    }

    private void SaveDraft()
    {
        Preferences.Set("draft_text", _editor.Text ?? string.Empty);
    }

    private void RestoreDraft()
    {
        _editor.Text = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDisappearing()
    {
        base.OnDisappearing();
        MessagingCenter.Unsubscribe<App>(this, "AppBackgrounded");
        MessagingCenter.Unsubscribe<App>(this, "AppResumed");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**

- **`Preferences`** is ideal for small text (up to ~1KB). For larger drafts, use `SecureStorage` or write to `FileSystem.AppDataDirectory`.
- **`Window.Deactivated`** fires reliably on iOS/Android when backgrounding.
- Unsubscribe in `OnDisappearing` to avoid leaks.
- Consider also saving on `TextChanged` with a debounce timer for crash resilience.

**Alternative (modern approach — no MessagingCenter):**

Replace `MessagingCenter` (deprecated in .NET 8+) with `WeakReferenceMessenger` from the CommunityToolkit.Mvvm package:

```csharp
// Send
WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Send(new AppBackgroundedMessage());

// Subscribe
WeakReferenceMessenger.Default.Register<AppBackgroundedMessage>(this, (r, m) => SaveDraft());
```
